    "Male), and E¬ g y is the average predicted score for the other group (e.g.",
    "Female), the lower the U PAR, the fairer the system.",
    "Meanwhile, S12, focusing on predicting success in law school, proposed Counterfactual Fairness.",
    "This approach is rooted in the idea that a predictor is considered counterfactually fair if, for any given context, altering a protected attribute (like race or gender) doesn't change the prediction outcome when all other causally unrelated attributes remain constant.",
    "Formally, let A denote protected attributes and the remaining attributes as X, while Y denotes the desired output."
